response.message:
@Aarobot I'm not "ignoring the possibility that a Q&amp;A site might not be the best tool for facilitating these discussions." Just because we disagree on the answer doesn't mean I haven't considered the question!

So, let's see what features you'd want in a site that WOULD host these discussions:

1) The ability of users to vote for on answers;

2) The ability to readily see the historical participation of the answerer, so that you can factor their profile into your interpretation of their answer;

3) The ability to suggest and accept edits to each other's answers;

4) The site structure lends itself to a solution of the "chat room/forum problem" (http://scobleizer.com/2009/11/02/the-chat-roomforum-problem-an-apology-to-technosailor/);

We could continue to list more, but I think this is sufficient to make the point. So now let's consider: Who has built a site like that? Well, StackExchange comes to mind - I can't say I've ever seen any others, but I certainly welcome suggestions!

On the other hand, I know that "StackExchange doesn't welcome (or even support)" this kind of question (http://meta.stackoverflow.com/questions/36818/would-you-recommend-stack-exchange-sites-vs-other-types-of-forum/36828#36828) - so I choose not to participate in any of the SE sites. But for you to assert that I "haven't considered" other tools just because I find the SE framework a GOOD SOLUTION to the problem of having lengthy "X vs. Y" debates is disingenuous in the extreme.
